<!-- Research Environment page  -->
<BaseLayout {pageTitle}>
    <ResearchTitle />
    <h2 class="text-4xl font-bold">{pageTitle}</h2>
    <article>
        <h3>
            Advances in PHA thin films formation applied to paper packagings
        </h3>
        <p>
            Nowadays, packaging materials are increasingly designed to minimize
            their impact on environment. Actually, packaging are made of
            petroleum-based plastics (PP,PE). Especially, paper-based packaging
            are covered with a thin film of PP/PE. This film confers barrier
            properties against gas and water to the paper, but removes the paper
            recyclability of the paper. Combined to the poor collection and
            recycling channels, there is a need to find new, greener alternative
            to those petroleum-based materials PHAs (PolyHydroxyAlcanoates) are
            a credible alternative when combined to cellulose-based substrates,
            since PHAs are bio-sourced and biodegradable, added to their
            excellent barrier properties. Therefore, a paper covered with PHA
            gains outstanding barrier properties (gas, water). Moreover, the
            PHA/paper packaging becomes fully recyclable. Since both PHA and
            paper are bio-sourced, a PHA/paper packaging will strongly
            contribute to a circular economy. We stand out from other PHA
            research by using powder rather than pellets, since the former is
            the native form of the PHA when extracted from bacteria
        </p>
        <h4 class="text-l font-bold">Results:</h4>
        <p>
            We developed three technologies to deposit PHA powder in a
            controlled fashion without any formulation nor additives in the PHA.
        </p>
        <p>
            We produced multi-layer structures (MLS) of PHBV/papers by a
            straightforward powder deposition methodology followed by
            conventional compression moulding. The use of the powder allows us
            to obtain thin films (&lt; 50µm) of PHBV of controlled thickness
            with a 30 µm thickness in average, for a weight of ca. 50 g/m². The
            MLS exhibited excellent water and oil barrier properties. The MLS’
            Cobb values were at least 15 times lower than the neat papers and 5
            times lower than other reported biopolymers. Moreover, the water
            vapour and oxygen barrier properties were in the range of reported
            biopolymers. While the water vapour and oxygen barrier properties
            are still far from their petro-sourced counterparts, we demonstrated
            that the MLS developed herein may be credible alternative to
            petro-sourced polymers, suitable for single use food packaging, such
            as food trays.
        </p>
        <p>
            Additive-free water/PHA solutions were found to be suitable to form
            thin films of PHA (&lt;10µm). We are in the process of patenting
            this straightforward process.
        </p>
        <p>
            Spary-drying of PHA in vortex turbines was found as an interesting
            deposition technology. Work is under progress to establish
            process/structure/properties of the deposited PHA layer
        </p>
        <section class="flex flex-row justify-around">
            <figure
                class="flex flex-col justify-center items-center text-center">
                <figcaption>
                    15x15cm² of PHA powder with a constant thickness
                </figcaption>
                <Picture
                    src="/assets/images/environment-1-1.png"
                    widths={[100, 150, 500]}
                    aspectRatio="1:0"
                    sizes="(max-width: 600px) 150px, 500px"
                    formats={["png"]}
