                <Picture
                    src="/assets/images/environment-1-2.png"
                    widths={[50, 200, 300]}
                    aspectRatio="1:0"
                    sizes="(max-width: 600px) 200px, 300px"
                    formats={["png"]}
                    alt="Home1"
                />
                <figcaption>
                    PHA film synthesized from additive-free water/PHA solutions
                    (patent pending).
                </figcaption>
            </figure>
            <figure
                class="flex flex-col justify-center items-center text-center">
                <Picture
                    src="/assets/images/environment-1-3.jpg"
                    widths={[100, 200, 350]}
                    aspectRatio="1:0"
                    sizes="(max-width: 600px) 200px, 350px"
                    formats={["jpg"]}
                    alt="Home1"
                />
                <figcaption>Spray-dried PHA powder</figcaption>
            </figure>
        </section>
    </article>
    <article>
        <h3>Synthesis of biodegradable PHA blends by reactive extrusion</h3>
        <p class="italic">Work in progress</p>
    </article>
    <article>
        <h3>
            Recycling and upscaling household thermoplastic waste (with a focus
            on milk bottles)
        </h3>
        <p>
            As a part of the European project RevalPET, I was in charge of the
            management of the 4th work package, which includes the coordination
            of the different partners to achieve the goal of the project, the
            redaction of reports on the results of the tests. The ambition of
            the project is to be able to produce high-performance materials from
            recycled wastes, in agreement with the environmental regulations
            REACH. From an experimental point view, the work package assigned
            require to evaluate the mechanical properties (tensile tests,
            fatigue) of the blends produced by the partners. In-situ digital
            image correlation and infrared thermography enable to monitor the
            damaging of the sample during a fatigue solicitation. Additional
            physic-chemical analysis (DSC, FTIR) are performed to elucidate the
            influence of cycled loading on the crystallinity of the blends.
        </p>
        <section class="flex flex-row justify-around">
            <figure
                class="flex flex-col justify-center items-center text-center">
                <Picture
